obalization and the requirements of social justice have been missing from the literature, education, and practice of these fields.This book provides an understanding of the economic and social dimensions of globalization, how globalization increases the interdependence of nations, the particular risks and opportunities it presents, and how some aspects of globalization can exacerbate oppression and marginalization. There are particular explorations of the challenges globalization presents in Africa and South America and a consideration of the special needs of children and families in the global context.This is a necessary volume. Its distinguished contributors have various perspectives on globalization, but all write to inform and assist the work of those whose vocation is to help others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalization -- Economic aspects. 0aGlobalization -- Social aspects. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspects. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aSocial justice. 0aSocial service. 4aEducation : Education. 4aPsychology : Psychotherapy. 4aSociology : Social Change. 4aSociology : Social Problems. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAustin, Sandra A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonpane III, Blase, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriar-Lawson, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriar-Lawson, Katharine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClaiborne, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Shirley J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Hal A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiva, Fernando, econtrib